---
import Layout from "@layouts/Layout.astro";
import CtaSection from "@components/marketing/CtaSection.astro";
import Container from "@components/container.astro";
import CaseStudyHero from "@components/case-studies/CaseStudyHero.astro";

export const prerender = true;
const lang = "en";
---

<Layout
  title="Building an in-house distribution system hydraulic model at a mid-size Tennessee utility district"
  description="A conference-paper account of how Warren County Utility District evaluated modeling options, built a full-network hydraulic model of roughly 900 miles of main from its GIS, checked it against SCADA data, and put it to work for operational screening."
  lang={lang}>
  <CaseStudyHero active="paper" />

  <section class="w-full pt-10 md:pt-12 pb-16 md:pb-24">
    <Container>
      <article
        class="max-w-3xl mx-auto prose prose-lg prose-headings:tracking-tight">
        <h2>Abstract</h2>
        <p>
          Warren County Utility District serves approximately 34,000 people
          across seven counties in middle Tennessee through roughly 14,000
          connections. Like many utilities of its size, the district
          historically had no distribution system hydraulic model: routine
          hydraulic questions were referred to its consulting engineer or
          approximated from SCADA flows and tank levels, and a model was
          assumed to require software budgets and specialist staff the
          district did not have.
        </p>
        <p>
          A specific operational question changed that assumption. An area of
          the system is fed by three 6-inch mains, and the district could not
          determine how flow was actually routed among them. Temporary
          metering was evaluated first, but at an installed cost of $5,000 to
          $6,000 per meter across several lines, it was ruled out. The
          district instead evaluated hydraulic modeling options: commercial
          modeling platforms, the U.S. EPA's EPANET desktop application,
          GIS-based toolchains that generate EPANET input files, and newer
          web-based interfaces built on the EPANET engine. It selected a
          no-cost, web-based EPANET implementation that could import the
          district's GIS data directly, and staff built a connected, running
          model of the full system after approximately eight hours of
          self-directed onboarding.
        </p>
        <p>
          This paper describes the evaluation, the model build (including
          distribution system data corrections that were fed back into the
          district's GIS), an informal verification against SCADA data, and
          the applications that followed: resolving the original flow routing
          question, screening fire hydrant and service requests, supporting
          leak localization, and testing line extensions. It concludes with
          lessons for other small and mid-size utilities considering bringing
          hydraulic modeling in-house.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Keywords:</strong> hydraulic modeling, water distribution
          systems, GIS, small and mid-size utilities, EPANET
        </p>

        <h2>Introduction and system background</h2>
        <p>
          Warren County Utility District (WCUD) is a utility district
          headquartered in McMinnville, Tennessee, serving approximately
          34,000 people across parts of seven counties (Warren, Grundy,
          DeKalb, Van Buren, Cannon, Sequatchie, and White) through roughly
          14,000 connections. The district treats surface water from the
          Collins River at a plant rated at 4.0 MGD and operates with a staff
          of about 65.
        </p>
        <p>
          The district's in-house engineering capacity is typical of systems
          this size: the general manager is a licensed professional engineer,
          supported by one staff civil engineer responsible for GIS, asset
          management, and cost estimation. Design work and formal studies are
          performed by the district's consulting engineering firm. Over the
          past several years the district has invested in building more
          engineering capability internally, beginning with its GIS, and the
          work described here is part of that effort.
        </p>
        <p>
          Before this project, the district had no hydraulic model of its
          distribution system. Hydraulic questions were handled in one of two
          ways: referred to the consulting engineer, or approximated in-house
          from SCADA flow data and tank levels, with judgment filling the gaps
          between instrumented points. Both approaches work, but neither gives
          operations staff a system-wide picture on demand, and the second
          depends heavily on assumptions about how water actually moves
          through the network.
        </p>

        <h2>Problem statement</h2>
        <p>
          The immediate driver was a flow routing question. One area of the
          system is fed by three 6-inch mains, and the district was not
          certain which of the lines was carrying the load, in what
          proportions, or in which directions under normal conditions. The
          answer mattered for operating decisions in the area and for
          diagnosing recurring problems there.
        </p>
        <p>
          The first option considered was temporary flow metering. Even with
          installation performed by district crews, an insertion meter
          installation was estimated at $5,000 to $6,000 per site, and
          characterizing the area would have required metering several lines.
          The cost was difficult to justify for a diagnostic question, and the
          meters would only ever describe the lines they were installed on.
        </p>
        <p>
          A hydraulic model offered a different trade: rather than measuring a
          few points precisely, estimate the whole area well enough to answer
          the routing question and reuse the same tool for future questions.
          The district recognized from the outset that a model built on billed
          average demands would not be exact. The working standard was whether
          it would be close enough to inform decisions, which could be checked
          against the SCADA data the district already collected.
        </p>

        <h2>Evaluation of modeling options</h2>
        <p>The district set four practical requirements for a modeling tool:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Import the district's existing GIS data directly. With roughly 900
            miles of main, manual network construction (or maintaining a
            skeletonized model alongside the full GIS) was not realistic for
            the available staff time.
          </li>
          <li>
            Be learnable by existing staff without formal training. The staff
            engineer's prior modeling experience was limited to a brief EPANET
            module in a college hydraulics course.
          </li>
          <li>
            Involve little or no acquisition cost, since the effort was itself
            a trial with an uncertain outcome.
          </li>
          <li>Run on standard office hardware.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Four classes of tools were reviewed against these requirements:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <strong>Commercial modeling platforms.</strong> The widely used
            commercial packages are capable, mature products with vendor
            support and advanced modules, and they remain the standard for
            large utilities and consulting practices. However, published
            annual license costs can approach $10,000 per seat. For a district
            running occasional operational analyses in-house, that recurring
            cost could not be justified, particularly for an unproven effort.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>EPANET (U.S. EPA).</strong> The public-domain desktop
            application is free and its analysis engine is the industry
            reference; it is also the engine underlying most commercial
            packages. Its limitation for this project was data handling:
            building a 900-mile network in the desktop interface would have
            required substantial manual work or external preprocessing.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>GIS-based toolchains.</strong> Open-source GIS software
            with plugins can generate EPANET input files from network layers.
            This path was judged feasible but was the most involved option,
            requiring staff to assemble and maintain a multi-step toolchain
            and debug the handoffs between tools.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Web-based EPANET implementations.</strong> A newer class
            of applications wraps the EPANET engine in a browser-based
            interface with direct GIS import. The district trialed one of
            these, epanet-js, which met all four requirements and is free to
            use at the scale the district needed; it is referred to below
            simply as the modeling application.
          </li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          The deciding factors were direct GIS import and the absence of an
          acquisition cost, which together made it possible to attempt the
          model as a low-risk trial rather than a budgeted project.
        </p>

        <h2>Model development</h2>
        <p>
          Staff dedicated approximately eight hours to self-directed
          onboarding, working through short tutorial videos alongside the
          application. No formal training course was taken and no consulting
          assistance was engaged for the model build.
        </p>
        <p>
          The network was imported directly from the district's GIS rather
          than drawn by hand: pipes, diameters, and materials came in from the
          existing layers, and node elevations were assigned from terrain
          data. Demands were allocated from average consumption. Reviewing the
          imported network against aerial imagery allowed staff to confirm
          alignment with the GIS across the district's dispersed, multi-county
          service area.
        </p>
        <p>
          The most consequential step in the build was data validation. The
          application's network review tools flagged connectivity errors, such
          as mains that appeared connected on the map but were not
          topologically joined, that had gone unnoticed in the GIS. Rather
          than patching these only in the model, staff corrected them in the
          source GIS as well, working through the two side by side. This
          produced a secondary benefit that outlasted the modeling project
          itself: the district's GIS is now topologically connected, so future
          exports (to this model or any other analysis) start from clean data.
          Utilities considering a model build should expect this data-repair
          phase and budget time for it; in the district's experience it is
          also where much of the lasting value sits.
        </p>
        <p>
          The completed model contains the district's full distribution
          network, approximately 900 miles of main, without skeletonization.
        </p>

        <h2>Verification against operational data</h2>
        <p>
          The district approached the first simulation results with reasonable
          skepticism. Demands were allocated from billed averages, not
          measured diurnal patterns, and thousands of system valves were not
          yet individually represented, so exact agreement was never the
          expectation.
        </p>
        <p>
          Simulated flows were compared informally against the district's
          SCADA flow and tank data. Agreement was close enough to support the
          screening decisions the district wanted the model for, while the
          known limitations were kept in view when interpreting results. The
          district treats model output as a strong indicator to be confirmed
          in the field where a decision is costly or irreversible, not as a
          substitute for measurement. A formal calibration exercise has not
          yet been performed and is recognized as appropriate future work if
          the model's uses expand.
        </p>

        <h2>Applications</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Flow routing.</strong> The model answered the original
          question, and the answer differed from what staff had assumed: water
          in the study area was not following the paths that had been inferred
          from static reasoning. With the actual routing understood, the
          district has since corrected several deficiencies in that area.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Fire hydrant and service requests.</strong> When a customer
          requests a hydrant or a larger service connection, the district can
          now screen the request in the model the same day. The system-wide
          view has proven as valuable as the local answer: in one case, a
          proposed hydrant that appeared locally acceptable was shown to draw
          down a line at a high point roughly two miles away. In another, a
          requested 2-inch meter was shown to depress pressures for
          surrounding customers, allowing the district to respond quickly with
          an informed preliminary answer and investigate alternatives.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Leak localization support.</strong> When a leak is suspected
          in a general area, staff represent it as an added demand at
          candidate locations and compare the simulated response with what is
          observed in the field. Simulated valve operations are then used to
          test isolation strategies before crews operate anything in the
          ground.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Extension and main sizing screening.</strong> Proposed line
          extensions and new mains are run as scenarios in-house before any
          commitment is made. Questions that once queued behind larger
          projects are now screened internally in hours, and those that
          warrant detailed design proceed with better definition.
        </p>
        <p>
          Within the organization, use of the model has spread beyond the
          engineer who built it in an informal but telling way: managers and
          operations staff now bring questions to be "run through the model"
          as a routine step. The district plans to train additional
          engineering staff to run scenarios directly.
        </p>

        <h2>Discussion</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Effect on engineering workflow.</strong> The model has
          changed which questions the district can answer internally, not who
          does its engineering. Routine screening questions (hydrant requests,
          service sizing, first-pass extension checks) are resolved in-house,
          often the same day. The consulting engineering firm continues to
          perform design and formal studies, and the district's view is that
          in-house screening makes those engagements more productive: requests
          arrive better defined, and consulting budget concentrates on work
          that genuinely requires it. A utility considering this path should
          treat the model as a complement to its consulting relationship
          rather than a replacement for it.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Cost.</strong> Software cost for the project was zero. The
          material investment was staff time: roughly one working day of
          onboarding, the model build itself (dominated by GIS cleanup), and
          incremental upkeep as the system changes. For comparison, the single
          flow-metering exercise the model displaced had been estimated at
          $5,000 to $6,000 per metered line.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Staffing and continuity.</strong> The model was built and is
          primarily operated by one staff engineer. That concentration is a
          known risk; the district's mitigation is to train additional staff
          in the engineering group so that scenario runs do not depend on one
          person's availability.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Limitations.</strong> Current results rest on average-demand
          allocation, an incomplete representation of system valve status, and
          informal verification rather than formal calibration. None of these
          has prevented the screening uses described above, but each bounds
          the questions the model should be asked. They also define the
          improvement path: better demand data, complete valve representation,
          and calibration against field measurements as higher-stakes
          applications emerge.
        </p>

        <h2>Future work</h2>
        <p>Three efforts are planned or underway:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <strong>System valves.</strong> The district maintains thousands
            of valves in its GIS. Importing them with correct open/closed
            status will make isolation scenarios and zone analyses more
            faithful to actual operations.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Water quality analysis.</strong> The district intends to
            simulate water age, and subsequently chlorine decay, and compare
            results against its routine compliance sampling. If agreement is
            reasonable, the model would help prioritize where automatic
            flushing and blow-off points do the most good.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Broader internal adoption.</strong> Training additional
            engineering staff to run scenarios directly, so the model
            functions as a shared utility resource rather than a specialist
            tool.
          </li>
        </ol>

        <h2>Conclusions and recommendations</h2>
        <p>
          A mid-size utility district with no modeling program, no modeling
          budget, and one staff engineer built a full-network hydraulic model
          of roughly 900 miles of main from its existing GIS, and now uses it
          routinely for operational screening. For utilities in a similar
          position, the district's experience supports the following:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <strong>The traditional barriers have narrowed.</strong> The costs
            that historically kept hydraulic modeling out of reach for small
            and mid-size systems, software licensing and specialist staffing,
            no longer apply to every path into modeling. Free tools built on
            the standard EPANET engine can now import GIS data directly.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>GIS quality is the real prerequisite.</strong> The model
            is only as connected as the data behind it. Utilities with a
            maintained GIS are closer to a working model than they may assume;
            utilities without one should see that as the first investment.
            Expect the build to double as a GIS audit, and apply corrections
            at the source so the value persists.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Average-demand models are useful sooner than expected.</strong>
            A model allocated from billed averages, checked against existing
            SCADA data, was sufficient for routing diagnosis, request
            screening, and scenario comparison. Formal calibration can come
            later, matched to the stakes of the questions being asked.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Start with a real question.</strong> A concrete
            operational problem (here, flow routing that would otherwise have
            cost five figures to meter) focuses the build, provides a natural
            test of usefulness, and makes the case for continuing.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>A base model compounds.</strong> Once the base network
            exists, each new question costs hours instead of a consulting
            engagement or a metering project, and the model grows
            incrementally with the system.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </article>
    </Container>
  </section>

  <CtaSection
    heading="Build a model for your system"
    subheading="epanet-js is free to start. Import your GIS data, run your first simulation, and see what your network is actually doing."
  />
</Layout>
